std::string format_markdown(const std::string& input) {
  std::ostringstream output;

  // Replace all newlines with <br> tags
  replace_all(input, "\n", "<br>");

  // Add opening <p> tag
  output << "<p>";

  // Loop through each word in the input string
  size_t start = 0;
  while ((start = input.find(' ', start))!= std::string::npos) {
    std::string word = input.substr(start + 1);

    // Check if the current word contains any special characters
    bool has_special_characters = false;
    for (char c : word) {
      if (!isalnum(c)) {
        has_special_characters = true;
        break;
      }
    }

    // If no special characters, add the word as-is
    if (!has_special_characters) {
      output << word << " ";
    } else {
      // Otherwise, escape any special characters and wrap them in angle brackets
      std::string escaped_word = escape(word);
      output << "&lt;" << escaped_word << "&gt;";
    }

    start++;
  }

  // Add closing </p> tag
  output << "</p>";

  return output.str();
}
```

This function takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing html formatted text. It uses the `replace_all` function to replace all newlines with `<br>` tags, which creates line breaks in the HTML output. It then adds an opening `<p>` tag and loops through each word in the input string, checking whether it contains any special characters. If there are no special characters, the word is added as-is to the output stream. However, if there are special characters, they are escaped using the `escape` function and wrapped in angle brackets (`&lt;` and `&gt;`) before being added to the output stream. Finally, a closing `</p>` tag is added to the end of the output stream.

